{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3648].
  {panel}

When JIRA Professional is fed a JIRA Enterprise license key, it is quietly accepted and generally runs fine.  However things can break, if for instance the user later tries to upgrade JIRA, and the JIRA upgrade task relies on the license to determine whether to apply an enterprise-only upgrade.  We should therefore prevent people from running JIRA Professional with an Enterprise key.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3633].
  {panel}

We should have a SOAP / HTTP service that can take the values passed from the commitinfo script and determine whether the commit is valid or not.

In most cases a valid commit needs a JIRA issue number, or some keywords ('refactoring', 'UI changes').

We can then write a perl/python/exe script to post that information from CVSROOT/commitinfo.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-3632].
  {panel}

I generally required to generate many issues at once. On these occasions, I do not necessary check that the issues I have created are actually created. However, in the situation where the disk space is full or at 100% usage on the server that we installed Jira, the cases are not being created. Since there is no warning or error message to warn that the disk space is, I only realize that all my cases that I thought I have generated did not. It will be nice if a warning or error message get generated in this situation.

